WEBVTT

00:07.574 --> 00:08.375
‐ Previously,
on "Resident Alien"...

00:09.209 --> 00:10.477
‐ My mission was simple:

00:10.477 --> 00:12.346
drop my device
onto their planet

00:12.346 --> 00:14.081
and head back home.

00:14.081 --> 00:17.217
I had no intentions of getting
close to any of them.

00:17.217 --> 00:19.486
[dramatic music]

00:19.486 --> 00:22.155
In order to complete
my mission,

00:22.155 --> 00:24.625
I would have to somehow fit in
with the human life forms.

00:24.625 --> 00:26.593
‐ Dr. Harry Vanderspeigle,
we had a murder

00:26.593 --> 00:27.794
in town last night.

00:27.794 --> 00:29.930
Need you to come down
and take a look at the body.

00:29.930 --> 00:31.465
‐ Sam Hodges was poisoned.

00:31.465 --> 00:34.434
He tried to give himself
a tracheotomy.

00:34.434 --> 00:37.070
‐ There is a killer out there.
We still need your help.

00:37.070 --> 00:38.939
‐ In a town of 1,000 people...

00:38.939 --> 00:40.541
‐ [screams]

00:40.541 --> 00:42.376
‐ There is a kid
who can see my true form.

00:42.376 --> 00:44.778
‐ You're just different.
I know what that feels like.

00:44.778 --> 00:47.714
Sometimes just feeling human
is alien to me.

00:47.714 --> 00:49.249
‐ Maybe there's
something redeemable

00:49.249 --> 00:50.651
about the human race
after all.

00:50.651 --> 00:52.219
[laughter]

00:52.219 --> 00:54.488
Unfortunately for them,
when I find my device,

00:54.488 --> 00:56.390
I will finally
complete my mission

00:56.390 --> 00:57.858
and kill them all.

00:57.858 --> 01:01.962
♪ ♪

01:01.962 --> 01:04.531
All beings of the universe
are different.

01:04.531 --> 01:07.267
For instance,
my people are brilliant.

01:07.267 --> 01:09.169
Humans, on the other hand,
are so dumb

01:09.169 --> 01:10.470
that they think
the leading cause of death

01:10.470 --> 01:13.073
is heart disease.
It's not.

01:13.073 --> 01:14.775
It's almond milk.

01:14.775 --> 01:17.844
Even the Grey aliens
won't touch the stuff.

01:18.579 --> 01:20.847
Despite their differences,
there is one truth

01:20.847 --> 01:23.083
that connects all beings.

01:23.083 --> 01:25.252
Life doesn't
ever go as planned.

01:25.252 --> 01:26.920
[shutter clicks]

01:26.920 --> 01:28.922
‐ [screams]

01:28.922 --> 01:31.925
[dramatic music]

01:31.925 --> 01:36.396
♪ ♪

01:36.396 --> 01:37.664
Whoa!

01:37.664 --> 01:39.700
[screams]

01:39.700 --> 01:40.667
[ethereal buzz]

01:40.667 --> 01:42.302
Oh!

01:43.136 --> 01:44.438
What the hell?

01:47.774 --> 01:49.776
[grunts]

01:49.776 --> 01:51.111
Help!

01:51.111 --> 01:53.013
Somebody!

01:54.414 --> 01:56.550
Help me!

01:56.550 --> 01:58.251
Help!

01:59.386 --> 02:00.721
Somebody!

02:02.956 --> 02:04.291
Help!

02:04.291 --> 02:07.227
[laidback acoustic strumming]

02:07.227 --> 02:14.301
♪ ♪

02:15.836 --> 02:17.971
‐ Finding an object
the size of a suitcase

02:17.971 --> 02:19.339
in the Colorado Mountains

02:19.339 --> 02:22.209
is like looking
for a needle in a haystack.

02:22.209 --> 02:23.877
I've been searching
for my device

02:23.877 --> 02:25.846
every day for months.

02:25.846 --> 02:27.347
I haven't found it yet,

02:27.347 --> 02:29.850
but after searching
a half dozen mountains,

02:29.850 --> 02:34.788
I finally found the haystack,
and that's all that matters.

02:34.788 --> 02:38.992
Well, that and being on time
for my first day of work.

02:38.992 --> 02:41.995
[upbeat music]

02:41.995 --> 02:44.731
‐ [screams]

02:47.968 --> 02:51.004
[continues screaming]

02:51.004 --> 02:54.408
‐ Max!
Max!

02:54.408 --> 02:55.275
Ugh!

02:55.275 --> 02:57.344
He went out the window.

02:57.344 --> 02:59.179
‐ Of course he did.

03:00.914 --> 03:03.483
‐ What the hell
happened in here?

03:03.483 --> 03:06.053
‐ The kid went nuts.
‐ What?

03:06.053 --> 03:07.487
Why?

03:09.156 --> 03:10.457
‐ I have no idea.

03:10.457 --> 03:12.626
I'm going to cut your head off!

03:12.626 --> 03:15.328
‐ [screams]

03:16.396 --> 03:18.165
‐ I think he has
emotional issues.

03:18.165 --> 03:20.400
‐ Well, we need to get
this place cleaned up.

03:20.400 --> 03:22.536
There hasn't been
a doctor on duty in days,

03:22.536 --> 03:24.871
and we have a bunch
of patients coming in.

03:24.871 --> 03:26.940
Well, don't just stand there.

03:26.940 --> 03:28.642
‐ Okay.

03:31.945 --> 03:33.213
‐ Ugh.

03:33.213 --> 03:34.281
‐ Max, okay.
‐ Count of three, bud.

03:34.281 --> 03:35.248
‐ You are getting filthy
under there.

03:35.248 --> 03:36.316
‐ Listen to your mother, Max.

03:36.316 --> 03:38.452
He's just looking
for my wallet.

03:38.452 --> 03:41.188
He's a good kid.
We're good parents.

03:41.188 --> 03:43.690
‐ The alien from my bedroom,
he's in there.

03:43.690 --> 03:45.292
He's the new doctor!

03:45.292 --> 03:47.060
‐ Okay.
‐ Max, I saw the new doctor.

03:47.060 --> 03:48.428
He didn't look
like an alien to me.

03:48.428 --> 03:50.030
‐ He's already gotten
inside your brain.

03:50.030 --> 03:50.931
‐ Come on, buddy.
‐ You're as good as dead.

03:50.931 --> 03:52.566
‐ Let's go.

03:52.566 --> 03:54.601
You are going back in there,
and you are letting that doctor

03:54.601 --> 03:56.036
take a look
at your sore throat.

03:56.036 --> 03:58.438
‐ And while I'm in there,
you can buy a four‐foot coffin.

03:58.438 --> 04:00.774
‐ Okay, look, that's enough.

04:00.774 --> 04:03.276
I cannot hear about
this alien stuff anymore,

04:03.276 --> 04:05.112
but he can come to work with me
and lie on the couch.

04:05.112 --> 04:06.880
If his throat
doesn't feel better,

04:06.880 --> 04:08.348
I'll bring him back, okay?

04:08.348 --> 04:12.018
‐ Oh, now you want to die too.
Make that three coffins.

04:12.919 --> 04:15.255
‐ [groans]
I'm serious.

04:15.255 --> 04:16.957
If he keeps this up,
we're getting rid of him.

04:16.957 --> 04:18.925
‐ Sounds good.
‐ [sighs]

04:18.925 --> 04:21.328
Oh, vanilla, thank God.
You I will keep.

04:21.328 --> 04:23.063
‐ Oh.
‐ Love you.

04:23.063 --> 04:26.366
[light dramatic music]

04:34.307 --> 04:36.376
‐ Whoa, whoa, what are you
doing with these?

04:36.376 --> 04:38.445
Look, do I need to remind you

04:38.445 --> 04:39.913
that this side
is the mayor's office

04:39.913 --> 04:41.815
and that side
is the sheriff's office?

04:41.815 --> 04:43.183
‐ We got a murder to solve.

04:43.183 --> 04:45.051
I got to make room
over there for murder stuff.

04:45.051 --> 04:48.522
‐ Yeah, well, there's no room
for those boxes in here, so...

04:48.522 --> 04:50.857
‐ Well, the laws of physics
would tend to disagree with you

04:50.857 --> 04:52.759
since there they are.

04:54.361 --> 04:56.797
‐ Sheriff, I'd like
to file a murder complaint.

04:56.797 --> 05:00.200
I know who killed Sam Hodges.
‐ What are you talking about?

05:00.200 --> 05:02.469
‐ Is that so?

05:02.469 --> 05:05.272
All right.
‐ Sure, have a seat.

05:05.272 --> 05:07.174
‐ Go ahead and lay it on me,
little deputy.

05:07.174 --> 05:09.810
‐ It's the new doctor.
He's an alien.

05:09.810 --> 05:12.279
‐ Okay, on that note,
I'm gonna need everyone out.

05:12.279 --> 05:13.814
Kid's a little delusional
with a fever.

05:13.814 --> 05:16.249
Maybe no talking for a day.
‐ Wait, wait, wait, wait.

05:16.249 --> 05:18.518
An alien?
What you mean?

05:18.518 --> 05:20.420
Like, he ain't got
a green card or something?

05:20.420 --> 05:24.391
‐ No, like, alien‐alien
from outer space.

05:24.391 --> 05:26.359
‐ Outer sp‐‐
‐ And shoot me.

05:26.359 --> 05:28.061
‐ What the hell are you
teaching this kid, huh?

05:28.061 --> 05:29.963
You know I could lock you up
for lying

05:29.963 --> 05:32.265
to an officer of the law?
That is a crime.

05:32.265 --> 05:34.668
You're committing crime.
‐ Got a sick kid, okay?

05:34.668 --> 05:36.670
Gonna need everyone out.
Got a sick kid.

05:36.670 --> 05:38.772
Just‐‐
‐ Yeah, he's sick all right.

05:38.772 --> 05:40.941
Let me ask you something.
You got HBO in your house?

05:40.941 --> 05:42.042
Here's what I want you to do.

05:42.042 --> 05:43.677
I want you
to watch "Oz" season one,

05:43.677 --> 05:45.412
and then come back and tell me
if you want to go to prison.

05:45.412 --> 05:47.414
Talking about some alien shit.

05:47.414 --> 05:49.916
I'ma go get me some more boxes.
‐ Uh, no.

05:49.916 --> 05:53.854
I really wish that you
wouldn't do that, Sheriff.

05:53.854 --> 05:55.755
‐ [whispers]
Okay, okay.

05:55.755 --> 05:59.392
Hey, I know the sheriff can
seem kind of mean sometimes,

05:59.392 --> 06:02.028
but he's just a teddy bear...

06:03.196 --> 06:05.899
With severe control
and anger issues.

06:05.899 --> 06:07.834
‐ But he didn't believe me

06:07.834 --> 06:09.502
when I told him
about the alien.

06:09.502 --> 06:11.571
Nobody does.

06:11.571 --> 06:15.075
‐ Well, look,
maybe he didn't believe you

06:15.075 --> 06:18.011
because he can't see
the alien, right?

06:18.011 --> 06:20.847
It's probably putting up
some kind of mind shield

06:20.847 --> 06:23.817
that only you can see through
because you're special.

06:23.817 --> 06:25.852
‐ Yeah, that makes sense.

06:26.786 --> 06:30.290
‐ One of my skills as a deputy
is to work as a sketch artist,

06:30.290 --> 06:32.225
so if you describe
the alien to me,

06:32.225 --> 06:33.693
I could draw a picture of him.

06:33.693 --> 06:35.729
‐ Great, then I
can get the word out!

06:35.729 --> 06:38.698
Okay, start with his eyes.

06:38.698 --> 06:41.167
They're, like, alien shape.

06:41.167 --> 06:43.169
And then he has
these scales going back‐‐

06:43.169 --> 06:44.771
like, blue scales
with little circles.

06:44.771 --> 06:45.906
‐ Ooh, okay.

06:45.906 --> 06:49.075
♪ ♪

06:49.075 --> 06:50.877
‐ Human doctors
have to go through years

06:50.877 --> 06:53.079
of medical school
to perform a procedure

06:53.079 --> 06:55.448
as simple
as burning off a wart.

06:55.448 --> 06:57.117
I was a scientist
on my planet,

06:57.117 --> 06:59.019
so this is easy for me.

06:59.019 --> 07:00.320
All I need is the Internet,

07:00.320 --> 07:02.222
and I can graduate
in five minutes.

07:04.791 --> 07:06.293
Okay.

07:07.360 --> 07:10.497
Let's take a look
at that nasty thing.

07:10.497 --> 07:12.032
Hm.

07:13.967 --> 07:17.137
You're not a 12‐year‐old boy
with a wart.

07:17.137 --> 07:19.873
‐ Mm, not a 12‐year‐old boy.
[chuckles]

07:19.873 --> 07:21.942
‐ Ah, yes, Harry, sorry.
This is Judy.

07:21.942 --> 07:23.510
She's in need of a pelvic exam.

07:23.510 --> 07:25.645
We had to move her up
from tomorrow.

07:25.645 --> 07:28.615
‐ Oh, okay.

07:28.615 --> 07:30.450
Pelvic exam.

07:34.921 --> 07:36.990
‐ So, big guy, you into sports?

07:36.990 --> 07:40.126
‐ No, but I am into
putting my pants back on

07:40.126 --> 07:42.028
before the breeze
dries out the lettuce.

07:42.028 --> 07:43.830
‐ Yeah, Harry,
she doesn't have all day.

07:43.830 --> 07:45.632
‐ Oh.
‐ I'll be right back.

07:45.632 --> 07:48.034
‐ Oh, yes.

07:48.034 --> 07:49.736
Of course.

07:54.407 --> 07:58.144
Okay, I see your problem.
You sat on an earring.

07:58.144 --> 07:59.546
‐ No!
That...

07:59.546 --> 08:01.815
‐ Sorry.
‐ That's supposed to be there.

08:01.815 --> 08:03.183
‐ Uh...

08:04.684 --> 08:05.952
Here we go.

08:05.952 --> 08:09.055
Let's just get
into this, mm‐hmm.

08:09.055 --> 08:10.824
Oh, yes, examining.

08:10.824 --> 08:13.893
Uh, yes.

08:13.893 --> 08:15.295
[shutter clicks]

08:15.295 --> 08:16.162
Oh, uh...

08:16.162 --> 08:17.864
‐ Did you just take a picture?

08:17.864 --> 08:19.666
♪ ♪

08:19.666 --> 08:21.301
‐ It was a selfie.

08:22.769 --> 08:24.337
My first day.

08:24.337 --> 08:27.040
‐ Huh.
[chuckles]

08:27.040 --> 08:28.575
[shutter clicks]

08:28.575 --> 08:30.844
‐ The day
didn't get any better.

08:30.844 --> 08:32.312
‐ Oh.

08:32.312 --> 08:36.816
‐ Well, it appears that you
are in excellent health.

08:36.816 --> 08:39.652
Concerning your breath,
did you recently eat

08:39.652 --> 08:41.721
a dead rodent?

08:41.721 --> 08:44.024
You should be
more careful next time.

08:44.024 --> 08:45.959
Your parents
don't have insurance,

08:45.959 --> 08:47.260
so if you get hurt again,

08:47.260 --> 08:49.162
they'll probably
lose their home

08:49.162 --> 08:51.064
and have to live
outside on the street.

08:51.064 --> 08:55.235
[light music]

08:56.469 --> 08:59.139
‐ She just found
a lump in her breast.

08:59.139 --> 09:00.240
Why don't you try to be

09:00.240 --> 09:02.642
a little more calming
this time?

09:02.642 --> 09:04.144
‐ I know what I'm doing.

09:07.013 --> 09:09.215
I see you found
a lump in your breast.

09:10.016 --> 09:11.217
‐ Yes.

09:11.217 --> 09:12.519
‐ I'm glad that you came in

09:12.519 --> 09:14.054
and that you've been
so diligent

09:14.054 --> 09:15.922
with your health.

09:15.922 --> 09:17.824
As you know, self‐examination

09:17.824 --> 09:19.459
along with
appropriate screenings

09:19.459 --> 09:21.661
can greatly increase
your odds of early detection,

09:21.661 --> 09:22.896
so I don't want you to worry.

09:22.896 --> 09:25.131
Many women find lumps
in their breasts all the time,

09:25.131 --> 09:27.934
and most of them
are nothing, okay?

09:27.934 --> 09:30.336
‐ Okay.
‐ Good.

09:30.336 --> 09:32.372
Now let's get
a look at that tit.

09:38.711 --> 09:42.048
I discovered that the woman
does not have cancer.

09:42.048 --> 09:44.284
I also discovered that "tit"

09:44.284 --> 09:46.886
is not the preferred term
for breast.

09:46.886 --> 09:49.389
‐ Hi.
‐ Hey.

09:49.389 --> 09:52.225
Harry, this is my father Dan.
Harry's a doctor.

09:52.225 --> 09:54.260
He's been helping us out
at the clinic.

09:54.260 --> 09:55.462
‐ Hello.

09:58.031 --> 10:00.567
‐ Sorry,
he doesn't like doctors.

10:03.236 --> 10:06.072
Dad, what are you doing?

10:06.072 --> 10:08.675
‐ I have a bad feeling.

10:08.675 --> 10:10.510
There's something
wrong with that man.

10:10.510 --> 10:13.446
‐ Oh, my God,
are you kidding me?

10:13.446 --> 10:14.981
You have a bad feeling
about every man

10:14.981 --> 10:16.316
within ten feet of me.

10:16.316 --> 10:17.917
‐ I don't have a bad feeling
about him.

10:17.917 --> 10:21.221
That's the problem.
‐ What are you talking about?

10:21.221 --> 10:25.391
‐ When I look at him,
I feel nothing at all.

10:25.391 --> 10:28.561
[soft dramatic music]

10:28.561 --> 10:31.197
♪ ♪

10:31.197 --> 10:34.000
‐ Asta's large father
does not like me.

10:34.000 --> 10:37.904
Can he somehow tell
I am different from them?

10:37.904 --> 10:40.240
This day cannot get any worse.

10:40.240 --> 10:42.609
[car horn honks]

10:42.609 --> 10:46.679
♪ ♪

10:46.679 --> 10:48.915
Shit.

10:48.915 --> 10:52.852
Oh, mm.

10:52.852 --> 11:00.026
♪ ♪

11:08.368 --> 11:08.668
[dramatic music]

11:10.904 --> 11:14.440
‐ This kid is a menace.
He just won't give up.

11:14.440 --> 11:15.875
Where was that effort
from the humans

11:15.875 --> 11:18.077
when we were helping them
build Stonehenge?

11:18.077 --> 11:20.613
A bunch of idiots just
sitting around drinking mead,

11:20.613 --> 11:24.050
making us do all the work.
Lazy druids.

11:24.050 --> 11:25.385
I can't leave.

11:25.385 --> 11:27.253
I'm too close
to finding my device,

11:27.253 --> 11:29.222
and I'm not turning
into someone else.

11:29.222 --> 11:32.458
It took me weeks to figure out
how to get this body to work.

11:32.458 --> 11:33.860
[Violent Femmes'
"Out the Window"]

11:33.860 --> 11:35.328
‐ ♪ Life was short
and life was sweet ♪

11:35.328 --> 11:37.297
♪ I was thinking
as I hit the street ♪

11:37.297 --> 11:38.464
♪ I could hardly believe ♪

11:38.464 --> 11:39.799
♪ I could scarcely conceive ♪

11:39.799 --> 11:41.534
♪ But I had
gone out the window ♪

11:41.534 --> 11:44.370
♪ I had gone out the window ♪

11:44.370 --> 11:47.974
♪ I had gone
out the window ♪

11:47.974 --> 11:49.742
♪ ♪

11:49.742 --> 11:54.681
♪ Oh, catch me,
we are falling ♪

11:54.681 --> 11:59.752
♪ Catch me, we are falling ♪

11:59.752 --> 12:02.989
♪ ♪

12:02.989 --> 12:04.324
[body thuds]

12:04.324 --> 12:05.625
‐ I have to be smart.

12:05.625 --> 12:07.327
I can't just kill this kid.

12:07.327 --> 12:09.128
It will draw
too much attention.

12:13.166 --> 12:17.470
[phone rings]

12:17.470 --> 12:19.138
‐ Hello?

12:19.138 --> 12:22.775
‐ [high‐pitched]
Hi, is Max there?

12:22.775 --> 12:24.344
‐ Who's this?

12:24.344 --> 12:27.380
‐ I'm a friend
of his from school.

12:27.380 --> 12:31.217
My name is...Elvis.

12:31.217 --> 12:34.988
‐ Yeah, okay.
Max, friend from school.

12:34.988 --> 12:38.524
‐ Hello?
‐ Hi.

12:38.524 --> 12:41.995
I saw your poster
on the street.

12:41.995 --> 12:44.230
[soft dramatic music]

12:44.230 --> 12:45.565
‐ Yeah?

12:45.565 --> 12:50.270
‐ And I saw that alien
on a bus leaving town,

12:50.270 --> 12:53.072
so you don't have
to worry about him anymore.

12:53.072 --> 12:55.174
[laughs unnaturally]

12:55.174 --> 12:57.543
‐ Are you sure it was him?

12:57.543 --> 13:02.048
‐ Yes, he was very handsome
like a young Jerry Orbach.

13:02.048 --> 13:03.850
‐ Who?

13:03.850 --> 13:06.252
Wait a minute,
I don't know you from school.

13:06.252 --> 13:08.755
‐ You're right.

13:08.755 --> 13:10.657
I'm a post office man.

13:10.657 --> 13:15.061
I'm good with my eyes,
and I saw that alien,

13:15.061 --> 13:16.996
and he's gone.

13:16.996 --> 13:19.699
‐ If you're a man,
why do you have a kid's voice?

13:19.699 --> 13:23.703
‐ Tricycle accident.
‐ Uh‐huh.

13:23.703 --> 13:26.539
If you work
at the post office,

13:26.539 --> 13:29.575
how much does a stamp cost?

13:30.877 --> 13:32.945
‐ $100.
‐ I knew it!

13:32.945 --> 13:35.581
You're him!
‐ $1,000.

13:35.581 --> 13:38.084
‐ I know it's you,
and guess what, alien,

13:38.084 --> 13:39.385
you can't kill me.

13:39.385 --> 13:41.287
My parents
know you're after me,

13:41.287 --> 13:43.690
and if I die,
they'll know you did it,

13:43.690 --> 13:44.824
and you're dumb.

13:44.824 --> 13:47.427
Stamps are, like,
30 bucks each, stupid.

13:47.427 --> 13:49.762
‐ [voice lowers]
Don't call me stupid...

13:49.762 --> 13:51.564
you little shit.

13:51.564 --> 13:52.465
‐ [gasps]

13:52.465 --> 13:55.335
S‐H‐I‐T is a bad word, stupid.

13:57.103 --> 13:58.571
[phone beeps]

13:58.571 --> 14:01.908
‐ That's it.
I'm going to kill him.

14:05.945 --> 14:08.881
[baby vocalizing]

14:08.881 --> 14:12.018
‐ What do you want?

14:12.018 --> 14:19.192
♪ ♪

14:23.162 --> 14:26.299
[baby laughs]

14:26.299 --> 14:28.334
‐ I didn't know babies
had a laugh button.

